<DIV id=3DRichEdit><TEXTAREA id=3Dtextarea tabIndex=3D3 name=3DpostBody =
rows=3D17 cols=3D47>&lt;a =
href=3D"http://www.onlamp.com/pub/a/onlamp/2004/05/06/writegreatcode.html=
"&gt;ONLamp.com: Why Learning Assembly Language Is Still a Good Idea =
[May. 06, 2004]&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp; This Slashdotted blurb by &lt;a =
href=3D"http://www.nostarch.com/greatcode.htm"&gt;Write Great =
Code&lt;/a&gt; author &lt;a =
href=3D"http://webster.cs.ucr.edu/"&gt;Randall Hyde&lt;/a&gt; is a =
lengthy paen to exceeding expectations and also understanding the =
performance that is possible in applications developed with an =
understanding of the underlying machine. =20

For me, this treatment is a bit overboard.&amp;nbsp; It works better, in =
my experience to consider (1) why and how to read machine language, (2) =
why and how to learn assembly language, (3) and who, what, when, where, =
how, and why to write assembly language in software delivered to someone =
else.

There is extensive discussion on the article, and numerous trackback =
links as well, so the article is a great resource. =20

I agree completely that a knowledge of machine architectures and what is =
probably happening underneath your higher-level programming system is =
valuable.&amp;nbsp;  It is often useful, as one commenter suggested, to =
read the assembler that some compilers will produce.&amp;nbsp; There are =
also settings where employment of assembly language is required, =
including computer forensic work and the creation of low-level elements =
such as BIOS software, Virtual Machine implementations, and certain =
high-performance library codes.

If someone asked me where to go to learn about machine language and how =
assemblers work, I would have them do something simpler than learn to =
work the native 80x86 system.&amp;nbsp; It is a little too much =
hands-free.&amp;nbsp;  I have two =
recommendations:&lt;ol&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;MIX =
First.&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp; Start with Donald E. Knuth's =
&lt;em&gt;Art of Computer Programming, vol. 1: &lt;a =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/readings/compsci.htm#[Knuth1997]"&gt;Fundamenta=
l Algorithms&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt; and use one of the simulators that are =
available for the MIX computer.&amp;nbsp; Check out the &lt;a =
href=3D"http://www-cs-faculty.stanford.edu/~knuth/mmix.html"&gt;MMIX =
computer&lt;/a&gt; that is being used for later volumes too.&amp;nbsp; =
The key takeaway from this treatment is learning to know what the =
performance of your software is, rather than believing the development =
tools assure it.&amp;nbsp; The next level of comprehension involves =
knowing when enough is enough.&amp;nbsp; For that, you need to know what =
the software is for and the context of usage that makes a particular =
level of performance important and sufficient.&amp;nbsp; Along with MIX =
and TAoCP,I would develop working familiarity with any popular scripting =
language for quickly expressing algorithms and learning how to test and =
perform the computational mathematics related to performance predication =
and analysis.&amp;nbsp; This also prepares for understanding the bridge =
between higher-level languages and the underlying =
machine.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;VM Next.&lt;/strong&gt;Learn =
a Virtual Machine Language.&amp;nbsp; My recommendation would be to work =
with the CLR of the &lt;a =
href=3D"http://developer.ximian.com/projects/mono/"&gt;Mono =
Project&lt;/a&gt;, since it follows the public ECMA specifications and =
interoperates with .NET.&amp;nbsp; There are ample materials and tools =
available for working with the Intermediate Language (the VM's "native" =
machine language), including assemblers and disassemblers.&amp;nbsp;  =
The use of a VM as an integration and just-in-time compilation vehicle =
provids for a rich experience.  It is an useful access to how Object =
Oriented Technology is being deployed these days.&amp;nbsp; Here is an =
excellent way to comprehend what this layer provides and how it sits =
between underlying physical machines and the abstractions that are =
enacted on behalf of higher-level programming systems.&amp;nbsp; Here, =
comprehension is understood better by understanding the use of compiled =
languages with the VM and my recommendation would be C# or any of the =
.NET-hosted languages that allow one to explore the blending of assembly =
language and other-language components in a coherent way.&amp;nbsp; It =
is also possible to build components in a native machine language and =
deliver them as VM-usable components, completing the story of where =
machine-language is usable.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;I am not adverse to =
programming the native machine, but one can't operate at the MS-DOS =
level forever, and there are many other considerations that are =
difficult to gain perspective on by starting from bare-bones assembly =
programming.&amp;nbsp; Simply put, it doesn't scale efficiently as a =
development methodology.&amp;nbsp; Sometimes the opportunity cost of =
exceeding expectations is just too high.
</TEXTAREA> </DIV>
